Data Visualization Project

Madison Pickett

5/8/2022

#Individual Data Visualization Assignment (Noted: I have uploaded all the datasets in the repo, but did not change the links, so they link back to a repo that is being used for my research.) This project looks at the glucose uptake of 231 (highly invasive) cancer cells on biomaterial meshes of different alignments. Our hypothesis is that as the alignment increases (becomes more aligned), the cancer cells will adopt a more invasive phenotype and trend toward glycolysis. A major marker of glycolysis is glucose uptake, which can be measured using NBD glucose (a fluorescent glucose analog). This experiment looks at NBD uptake at a per cell level, at two different time points (Day 3 and Day 5). A python script was used to process the images, where many parameters concerning the NBDs properties were measured. We were specifically looking at the integrated intensity per cell. The number of cells was characterized by the number of Draq5 nuclei counted by the script (Draq5 is a fluorescent nuclear dye). From here the average intensities per cell were calculated on a per image basis and then by a per condition basis (Random, Aligned, Random Matrigel, Aligned Matrigel) for each biological replicate (n=2) and technical replicate (N=3).

Random Matrigel N=2 (Day 3)

library(tidyverse)
##  Attaching packages  tidyverse 1.3.1 
##  ggplot2 3.3.5      purrr   0.3.4
##  tibble  3.1.6      dplyr   1.0.7
##  tidyr   1.1.4      stringr 1.4.0
##  readr   2.1.1      forcats 0.5.1
##  Conflicts  tidyverse_conflicts() 
## x dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
## x dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(cowplot)
## DAY 3, AM, N2, 231
n1<- "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mrpickett26/NBD_glucose_Analysis/main/MyExptN2_231_AM_Day3NBDglucose.csv"
d_nbd_n2_AM_231<-read_csv(n1, col_names=TRUE)  #load in the NBD dataset
## Rows: 5547 Columns: 77
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr  (4): FileName_Draq5, FileName_NBDglucose, PathName_Draq5, PathName_NBDg...
## dbl (73): ImageNumber, ObjectNumber, AreaShape_Area, AreaShape_BoundingBoxAr...
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
d1<- "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mrpickett26/NBD_glucose_Analysis/main/MyExptN2_231_AM_Day3Draq5_nucleus.csv"
d_draq_n2_AM_231<-read_csv(d1, col_names=TRUE) #load in the Draq5 dataset
## Rows: 1682 Columns: 77
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr  (4): FileName_Draq5, FileName_NBDglucose, PathName_Draq5, PathName_NBDg...
## dbl (73): ImageNumber, ObjectNumber, AreaShape_Area, AreaShape_BoundingBoxAr...
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
#Group the NBD thresholded fluorescence intensity by the image number or its respective image, then calculate the mean intensity of the integrated intensity within that image 
d_nbd_n2_AM_231_meanint<- d_nbd_n2_AM_231%>%
  group_by(ImageNumber)%>%
  summarize(meanIntnbd1= mean(Intensity_IntegratedIntensity_NBDglucose, na.rm=TRUE))

#Group the Draq5 thresholded fluorescence intensity by the image number or its respective image, then calculate the number of Draq5 objects 
d_draq_n2_AM_231<- d_draq_n2_AM_231%>%
  group_by(ImageNumber)%>%
  summarize(n=n())

#Calculate the the mean intensity of the NBD per cell
mean_N2_231_AM_Day3<- d_nbd_n2_AM_231_meanint$meanIntnbd1/d_draq_n2_AM_231$n

#Calculate the the mean intensity of the NBD per image
mean_tot_N2_231_AM_Day3<- (sum(d_nbd_n2_AM_231_meanint$meanIntnbd1/d_draq_n2_AM_231$n))/nrow(d_nbd_n2_AM_231_meanint)

d2<- "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mrpickett26/NBD_glucose_Analysis/main/MyExptN2_231_RM_Day3Draq5_nucleus.csv"
d_draq_n2_RM_231<-read_csv(d2, col_names=TRUE)
## Rows: 1357 Columns: 77
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr  (4): FileName_Draq5, FileName_NBDglucose, PathName_Draq5, PathName_NBDg...
## dbl (73): ImageNumber, ObjectNumber, AreaShape_Area, AreaShape_BoundingBoxAr...

  group_by(ImageNumber)%>%
  summarize(n=n())

#plot the data

##Actual Data Visualization #The data visualization can probably be spiced up a bit it is still relatively boring data. I was orgininally wanting to do something more interactive that would change intensity of brightness, but wasnt really sure how it would be applicable to what I wanted to represent. The samples that included the matrigel coating are more similar to the breast microenvironment and are more supportive of cellular proliferation meaning there are a lot more cells per image. One issue with the script and this dataset is that when we are imaging, the z-planes of going through the scaffold can produce a lot of background fluorescence from the cells that are embedded in the scaffold (fluorescing in a different z plane). I thought it would be cool to do something where the number of cells and intensity was represented on a single plot. My best option was looking at a heat map where we can colormetrically represent the intensity and represent the number of cells per image using the size of the data points.

#Need to rearrange some of the data to make it easier to plot in this way
